<p>Quite often I have an <code>if</code> statement where I have two cases, one of which requires a one-liner and one of which needs lots of code to be dealt with. From a readability point of view, which should I put first, given that I don't know how likely each one is? So:</p>  <pre><code>if(flag) {     // lots and lots and lots of code     // blah     // blah     // blah     // blah     // blah     // blah     // etc } else {     // easy one liner } </code></pre>  <p>compared to</p>  <pre><code>if(!flag) {     // easy one liner } else {     // lots and lots and lots of code     // blah     // blah     // blah     // blah     // blah     // blah     // etc } </code></pre>  <p><strong>Note</strong>: This is not a performance question, but a readability/ease of maintenance one.</p>